=C2=A0=

Correct. These paths get one started in the walk towards the same end poin=
t - Self-realization.

=C2=A0
> To be free is to be awakened.
=C2=A0
Not ex=
actly. Awakening is just a step towards freedom. Freedom comes in the end a=
fter walking a path for enough time after awakening.
=C2=A0
An unawakened s=
adhaka practicing jnana yoga reads books and talks eloquently about how eve=
rything is god, but looks at different people, objects and experiences with=
 a different attitude. He becomes happy (if not externally, atleast interna=
lly) when people praise him and becomes upset when people criticize him, an=
d so on. An awakened sadhaka practicing jnana yoga starts to honestly conte=
mplate one's actions, words, thoughts (and even instincts finally) and slow=
ly weeds out conditioning that makes one look at different transient things=
 differently. As his equanimity increases, still there will be episodes of =
getting carried away. As he employs contemplation and self-correction more =
and more, such episodes will become less and less frequent and one will bec=
ome liberated in the end.
=C2=A0
An unawakened sadhaka practicing karma yog=
a passionately engages in dharmik actions for the benefit of others. He get=
s elated and feels proud when good results come and becomes upset when bad =
results come. An awakened sadhaka practicing karma yoga starts to have deta=
chment to results. When something happens which makes him elated, proud, as=
hamed or upset, he will not think much about it, take it as god's prasad an=
d think about what is the right action for him right now. As his detachment=
 increases, still there will be episodes of getting carried away. As one be=
comes more and more detached (to results of actions), such episodes will be=
come less and less frequent and one will become liberated in the end.
=C2=
=A0
An unawakened sadhaka practicing raja yoga goes through yama, niyama, p=
ratyahara, dhyana, dharana etc. His psychic life force may even arise and a=
scend. He may have various experiences and may feel proud or become attache=
d to them. An awakened sadhaka practicing raja yoga will not not lose self-=
control in the face of anything and will keep the focus on samadhi. He will=
 not be distracted by anything that comes on the way and keep perfecting co=
ncentration and self-control so that samadhi (deep concentration on the unc=
onditioned Self) comes. In the beginning, one may be in samadhi state now a=
nd then. As practice is perfected, one can be in it all the time and become=
 liberated.
=C2=A0
An unawkened sadhaka practicing bhakti yoga is devoted t=
o god and worships him/her as much as one can, but will project his ego, co=
nditioning and desires onto his worship and hence onto the god he worships.=
 For example, he may think "I worship the highest god while that person wor=
ships a lower god. I am better" or "I am worshipping god everyday. I will g=
et so and so result" or "I worship god more than that person. I am better".=
 An awkened sadhaka practicing bhakti yoga has little expectation, pride et=
c. Worship becomes not about him but about god! He worships god and marvels=
 at the power that holds this cosmos together - the power that runs things =
infinitismally smaller than a boson and infinitely larger than a galaxy. He=
 will look at himself as a fully insignificant particle in front a supreme =
power. His desires, likes, dislikes, conditioning and agendas start to seem=
 too insignificant in front of contemplating about that supreme power. Even=
 as that
 devotional spirit increases, there will be episodes when one beco=
mes self-centered in one's worship. But with practice, one loses oneself co=
mpletely and surrenders completely to the supreme power and become liberate=
d in the end.
=C2=A0
In each path, one may walk the path without making any=
 significant progress for a long time. As one starts to imbibe the inherent=
 qualities of the path, some internal transformation will kick in. Yet, the=
 force of prior conditioning, coming from many lives, is too strong to over=
come. One keeps walking..
